english:
  title: Record of the Pavilion of Pure Fragrance
  author: Lee Sek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My uncle, the retired official of the Ministry of Personnel, planted lotus flowers in a small pond and wished to build a pavilion beside it. He sent word asking me to name it and write this record. I, Sek, am recovering from illness and find myself yearning only for the clarity of mind that Zhu Xi of Shaoyang possessed—that clarity of wind-swept light and moonlit sky. So I have taken his words that "fragrance grows purer with distance" and set down their meaning.

    When Heaven and Earth first divided, the light and pure ascended above, while when human beings came into being, those who received this vital force in full became sages and worthies. In the governance of states, such fragrant virtue stirs the divine and luminous, and this can be seen even in the flourishing ages of the Three Dynasties. Zhu Xi, living in Song's age of cultural brilliance, mourned the calamities brought by the chaos and obstruction of the Five Dynasties. He illuminated the profound principles of the Supreme Ultimate from the sacred classics, thereby continuing the transmission from Confucius and Mencius. His devotion to this was so complete that he wrote his Essay on Loving the Lotus to expound it. Yet even this seemed to him incomplete, so he concluded with the words: "Who else loves the lotus as I do?" Thus across a thousand empty years his call awakens those who would learn.

    I, in my graying years, have pursued the classics with reverence and admiration. How fortunate that my uncle shares this love with Zhu Xi! My joy at this exceeds my usual manner. I imagine when the local worthies and their guests arrive, raising cups and composing linked verses, with waters clear on fair days and lotus banks beneath the rain, with wind-turned leaves and mist-wrapped buds—scenes that seem like paintings yet are not paintings, like poems yet are not poems. Gray-faced and white-haired, they would sing and dance among these waters as if they were the people of the age of Ge Tian or the era of Fu Xi himself. The heart at peace, the body at ease, the vital force complete and the spirit serene—not merely the lotus flower's purity, but my uncle's pure virtue will spread ever further as a legacy to his descendants.

    In future days, when I retire from office and return to settle nearby, gaining a corner plot of land, I will be able to join him on his walks, and then I will compose verses anew in his honor.

    Written nine days before the winter solstice in the Year of the Wood Horse.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhu Xi (周濂溪), known as Shaoyang (舂陵), was an eleventh-century Neo-Confucian philosopher whose "Essay on Loving the Lotus" (愛蓮說) became a classical text praising the lotus as a symbol of moral purity and virtue unsullied by worldly corruption.
  - key: ''
    value: The "light wind and moonlit sky" (光風霽月) is a classical expression for clarity of mind and spiritual purity, originally used by Zhu Xi to describe an ideal state of consciousness.
  - key: ''
    value: The Five Dynasties (五季) refers to the period of political fragmentation and disorder that preceded the Song Dynasty, viewed by Confucian scholars as a time of moral decay.
  - key: ''
    value: The references to the ages of Ge Tian (葛天氏) and Fu Xi (羲皇氏) evoke legendary periods of golden simplicity and harmony in Chinese mythology, suggesting an idealized state of natural human flourishing.
